<HEADLINE>
<P>
LAKERS' WORTHY PLEADS NO CONTEST TO SOLICITING AND IS FINED $1,000 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARK HEISLER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
James Worthy has pleaded no contest to two misdemeanor charges of soliciting 
prostitution in Houston. 
</P>
<P>
He was fined $1,000, ordered to perform 40 hours of community service and 
placed on deferred adjudication probation for one year. 
</P>
<P>
If he meets the terms of his probation, both charges will be dismissed. 
</P>
<P>
Worthy had pleaded not guilty at his arraignment. The new plea was entered 
Thursday in Houston by Worthy's attorney, Cornel Williams. Sentence was 
pronounced by visiting County Court-at-Law Judge Bob Moen. 
</P>
<P>
Worthy was arrested on Nov. 15, before the Lakers' game against the Rockets. 
Houston police said he had called an escort service that they monitor, and they 
sent two officers posing as escorts. They reported that Worthy proposed a 
transaction for sex, and arrested him. 
</P>
<P>
The Lakers said they had no comment. Worthy has declined to comment since the 
arrest. MARK HEISLER 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
WORTHY, JAMES; BASKETBALL PLAYERS; SENTENCING; PLEAS; PROSTITUTION -- TEXAS 
</P>
